'''Brava Creole''' is the name given to the variant of [[Cape Verdean Creole]] spoken mainly in the [[Brava, Cape Verde|Brava Island]] of [[Cape Verde]]. It belongs to the [[Sotavento Creoles]] branch. The speakers of this form of Capeverdean Creole are 8,000 (1.36% of the national population){{Fact|date=April 2007}}. One of the least spoken being seventh place and one of the firsts to have written literature, in which [[Eugénio Tavares]] wrote some of his poems.
==Characteristics== Besides the main characteristics of [[Sotavento Creoles]] the Brava Creole has also the following ones: * The progressive aspect of the present is formed by putting ''stâ'' before the verbs: '''''stâ'' + V'''. * The sound that originates from Portuguese {{IPA|/ɐ̃w/}} (written ''ão'') is {{IPA|/ɐ̃/}} rather than {{IPA|/õ/}}. For example, ''coraçã'' {{IPA|/koɾɐˈsɐ̃/}}, not ''coraçõ'' {{IPA|/koɾɐˈsõ/}} “heart”; ''mã'' {{IPA|/ˈmɐ̃/}}, not ''mõ'' {{IPA|/ˈmõ/}} “hand”; ''razã'' {{IPA|/ʀɐˈzɐ̃/}}, not ''razõ'' {{IPA|/ʀɐˈzõ/}} “reason”.
